==English==

===Pronunciation===
*ro͞ot, {{IPAchar|/ruːt/}}, /<tt>ru:t</tt>/
*{{audio|en-us-root.ogg|Audio (US)}}
====Homophones====
*[[route]]

===Etymology===
From Middle English '''root''' (underground part of a plant) < late Old English '''[[rōt]]''' < Old Norse '''[[rōt]]''' < Proto-Germanic '''[[*wrot]]''' < Proto-Indo-European '''[[*wrd-]]''' (root). Cognate with [[wort]] and [[radix]].

====Noun====
'''root''' (''plural:'' '''[[roots]]''')
# The part of a plant, generally underground, that absorbs water and nutrients.
# The part of a tooth extending into the bone holding the tooth in place.
# Source.
#: ''The love of money is the root of all evil''
#{{mathematics}} Of a number or expression, a number which, when raised to a specified power, yields the specified number or expression; the [[square root]] is understood if no power is specified (in which case, ''the root of'' is often abbreviated to ''root'').
#: ''The cube root of 27 is 3.''
#: ''Multiply by root 2.''
#{{mathematics}} A [[zero]] (of a [[function]]).
#{{mathematics}} A designated [[node]] in a [[tree]].
#(''philology'') A word from which another word is derived.
#(''Australian coarse slang'') An act of [[sexual intercourse]].
# (''Australian coarse slang'') A sexual partner.
#{{computing}} the parent of all nodes of a tree structure. 
#{{computing}} [[UNIX]] terminology used to refer to the first user account with complete access to the operating system and its configuration, found at the root of the directory structure. Also is the word generally used to refer to the person who manages accounts on a [[UNIX]] system.

=====Usage notes=====
For the Australian sexual senses, ''root'' is somewhat milder than ''[[fuck]]'' but still quite coarse, certainly not for polite conversation.  The normal usage is ''have a root'' or similar, and generally no confusion or [[double entendre]] arises in other uses like "tree root" or "root cause".

=====Synonyms=====
*(''source''): [[basis]], [[origin]], [[source]]
*(''zero of a function''): [[zero]]
*(''word from which another is derived''): [[etymon]]
*(''act of sexual intercourse''): [[screw]] (''UK, US''), [[shag]] (''UK'') ; ''see also'' [[WikiSaurus:sexual intercourse]]
*(''sexual partner''): [[screw]] (''UK, US''), [[shag]] (''UK'')

