===Etymology===
From Middle English '''[[wrōten]]''' (to dig with the snout) < Old English '''[[wrōtan]]''' < Proto-Germanic '''[[*wrotanan]]''' (to dig out, root) < Proto-Indo-European base '''[[*red-]]''' (to scrape, scratch, gnaw). Cognate with [[rodent]].

====Verb====
'''to root''' ([[roots]], [[rooted]], [[rooting]])

#To [[rummage]], to search as if by digging in soil, to root out.
# {{US}} To [[cheer]] or similar to support a sports team (or similar).
#(''Australian coarse slang'') To have [[sexual intercourse]].

=====Usage notes=====
For the Australian sexual sense, ''root'' is somewhat milder than ''[[fuck]]'' but still quite coarse, certainly not for polite conversation.  The sexual sense will often be understood, unless care is taken with the context to make the [[rummage]] sense clear.  Confusion often arises with the US sports sense, so to speak of "rooting for the team" sets Australians [[giggle|giggling]].  The past participle ''rooted'' is equivalent to ''[[fucked]]'' in the figurative sense of broken or tired, but ''rooting'' is only the direct verbal sense, it isn't an all-purpose intensive like ''fucking''.  

=====Synonyms=====
*(''rummage''): [[dig out]], [[root out]], [[rummage]]
*(''cheer''): [[barrack]] (''Britain'', ''Australia'', ''New Zealand'')
*(''have sexual intercourse''): [[screw]] (''US''), [[shag]] (''British'') - See [[WikiSaurus:sexual intercourse]]

